# Introduction to Object-Oriented Programming

Object-oriented programming (OOP) organizes code around **objects** â€” bundles of data and the functions that operate on that data. Before classes, you wrote free functions that acted on variables passed in as arguments. OOP flips that relationship: the data and its behavior live together in one unit.

The three core ideas underpinning OOP are:

- **Encapsulation** â€” hiding internal state and exposing only what callers need
- **Inheritance** â€” building new types by extending existing ones
- **Polymorphism** â€” treating different types through a shared interface

This chapter focuses on **classes**, C++'s primary tool for defining your own types.

## Classes vs. Structs

A `class` groups member variables (data) with member functions (methods). In C++, `struct` and `class` are nearly identical â€” the only built-in difference is default access: `struct` members are `public` by default, `class` members are `private`. In practice, `struct` is conventionally used for simple data aggregates, and `class` for types with meaningful behavior and invariants.

## A Minimal Example

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

struct Book {
    std::string title;
    int pages{};

    void print() const {
        std::cout << title << " (" << pages << " pages)\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    Book b{"Clean Code", 431};
    std::cout << b.title << '\n';
    b.print();
}
```

`Book` has two public member variables and one member function. Because this is a `struct`, all members are public by default. The object is created using **aggregate initialization** â€” the `{"Clean Code", 431}` syntax fills in the members in declaration order.

The `const` qualifier on `print()` is a promise: calling this method will not modify the object. Get into the habit of marking any method that only reads data as `const` â€” it communicates intent and enables the compiler to catch accidental mutations.

## Why This Matters

Without OOP, related data drifts apart across your codebase. A `Book` might become three separate variables managed by scattered functions, with nothing preventing callers from putting the page count at -500. Classes centralize that data and â€” in upcoming lessons on access specifiers and constructors â€” will let you enforce rules about it.

Upcoming lessons in this chapter will cover member functions in depth, access specifiers, constructors, and how to design a class interface that's hard to misuse.

